00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:20.580
We need to orient ourselves. We should
answer a basic question: What is a game?

00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:24.760
The dictionary will tell you 'a game
is a construct that organizes play

00:01:24.780 --> 00:01:28.920
through a series of rules for the purpose of
achieving a set of goals overcoming an

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:34.040
obstacle and/or attaining an objective'.
That's a decent definition. I would call

00:01:34.040 --> 00:01:38.440
games "entertainment" but they're a very
specific kind of "entertainment".

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:42.460
Game designer Chris Crawford came up
with a really cool hierarchy to explain this.

00:01:42.460 --> 00:01:47.720
To start, Crawford characterizes any kind
of interactive entertainment as a play thing;

00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:50.400
anything that you interact with to entertain yourself qualifies.

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:56.260
But there are also two types of playthings:
a play thing without a goal like a slinky is a toy,

00:01:56.260 --> 00:02:00.820
but when there's a goal involved like trying to get the slinky down the stairs, Crawford calls that a challenge.

00:02:00.820 --> 00:02:08.240
Now if you're working to complete this challenge with no other active agent or person involved, it turns out you're working on a puzzle.

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:12.000
But when there is some kind of second party involved, then you have a conflict.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:17.320
Ok, we're almost there. Crawford subdivides
conflicts into competitions and games.

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:20.980
In a competition the participants don't
interact or interfere with each other.

00:02:20.980 --> 00:02:26.000
A good example of a competition is figure skating.
Everybody's skating to win but they

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.640
can't really affect each other's
performances.

00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:34.540
Well, except for that one time with Tonya Harding and Nancy Kerrigan but, you know, look it up.

00:02:34.540 --> 00:02:40.800
Mario Kart though, now that's a game. Players interact continuously, blocking and passing, and there's no

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:45.220
clearer example of interference than when you're
in first place and one of your friends in 8th place

00:02:45.220 --> 00:02:48.880
and they use a blue shell and take you out and take the leap. Why do you always do that to me, Katie?

00:02:48.880 --> 00:02:51.960
It's not cool! And here's an
interesting thing to think about:

00:02:51.960 --> 00:02:55.520
You don't have to be playing against a
person for something to be a game.

00:02:55.520 --> 00:02:59.480
Those soldiers blocking your path in Metal
Gear are artificial intelligence or AI

00:02:59.489 --> 00:03:02.790
agents trying to stop you from
accomplishing your goal.

00:03:02.790 --> 00:03:06.070
The rules of solitaire can be
constructed as an agent working to stop you

00:03:06.070 --> 00:03:10.320
from completing the game. So games have
goals like scoring points or saving the

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:13.000
princess and we achieve those goals by
following the rules,

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:17.280
like moving our game piece six places if we roll a six on the die or ending

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:21.820
our turn if we've spent all of our mana. Of course
none of this matters unless you want to play.

00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:28.740
Voluntary participation is essential, otherwise it's work.
I'd also like to get at why we play games,

00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:33.260
but that's a little harder. The short answer is,
there is no short answer. There is no

00:03:33.270 --> 00:03:37.610
universal unified theory of why we play
games. There's no constitution of gaming,

00:03:37.610 --> 00:03:41.580
no ten commandments of gaming. Different
games work on our brains in different ways.

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:49.120
Games like Tetris appeal to our desire to create order. Something like Animal Crossing lets us be the center of a whole tiny universe.

00:03:49.120 --> 00:03:54.220
Games like World of Warcraft or Destiny
let us live a remarkable life in another world.

00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:58.800
Games like Candy Crush lets us crush candy.
We play games for a lot of different reasons.

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:03.160
Let's leave behind the mystery of why we
play for a while and talk about what can

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:06.460
a game be and what can a game do. Take
video games.

00:04:06.460 --> 00:04:09.480
Modern video games can be a bit
formulaic but recent technological

00:04:09.480 --> 00:04:13.410
advances have made games available to a
wider audience and they've made the

00:04:13.410 --> 00:04:20.200
tools to create games widely available
and that's well... a game-changer! Get it?

00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:25.110
A game-changer! You see cause we're talking
games. A larger audience and a larger pool

00:04:25.110 --> 00:04:29.360
of creators means a wider variety of
games that get produced. Sure, you'll get

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:33.700
Call of Duty and the annual licensed NFL
game that cost millions to make and sells millions

00:04:33.700 --> 00:04:37.590
of copies but more gamers and lower
production and distribution costs means

00:04:37.590 --> 00:04:41.810
quirky games like Braid or Super Meat Boy
or Shovel Knight. Games that might have

00:04:41.810 --> 00:04:45.780
relatively small audiences can be
profitable and sometimes those quirky

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:50.370
independent games can get so profitable
and so popular that soon they hit a wide

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:55.440
audience just as much as a Triple A title.
And when I say wide audience I mean WIDE audience.

00:04:55.440 --> 00:05:01.200
In the United States alone there are
around 145 million video game players.

00:05:01.200 --> 00:05:07.040
37% of those players are over the age
of 36 and 18% are under 18.

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:12.180
That kind of breaks the gamers stereotype, doesn't it? And increasingly games are part of players' daily lives.

00:05:12.180 --> 00:05:18.160
According to video game academic Jane McGonigal by 2010 the average video game player in the US

00:05:18.169 --> 00:05:23.389
played for 22 hours a week. That's like watching
all the Harry Potter movies in order,

00:05:23.389 --> 00:05:28.860
and then watching Chamber of Secrets again every week! That's a dedicated Harry Potter fan.

00:05:28.860 --> 00:05:33.820
Clearly we're spending a lot of time playing video games so what's this doing to us?

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:40.920
We now have entire schools devoted to gaming and almost every major university offers classes and degrees related to games.

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:44.260
The University of Southern California, University of Utah, and Savannah College

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:49.480
of Art and Design all have renowned programs
in game art, programming, and design.

00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:53.020
The gaming industry makes so much money. Even
more sometimes than movies and television!

00:05:53.020 --> 00:05:55.610
There are even people right now on
YouTube

00:05:55.610 --> 00:06:00.810
who are making a living playing video
games, on camera - that's a job! And it's not just

00:06:00.810 --> 00:06:05.090
about learning how to make games or make
money off of games. Massively multiplayer

00:06:05.090 --> 00:06:10.760
game worlds can provide insights across disciplines. Sociologists can study how people form groups.

00:06:10.760 --> 00:06:13.140
Economists can finally see if their models work.

